I write all of this to show that even though the person who had an eating disorder may be in recovery or even recovered, the damage done to the body lingers. 

My eating disorder was never about weight. I simply couldn't stomach what was done to me as a child.
I am still waiting results on why my heartburn can't be controlled, why I sometimes shoot out stomach acid like the dinosaur in Jurassic Park.

Just yesterday I had an Esophageal Manometry, which is a test to see how well the esophagus is working to swallow food.
 
For this test they shoved a catheter of about three feet up my nose, down my esophagus, and into my empty stomach while I was awake.

Since starting recovery nine years ago, I have had four upper GI scopes, have been to the emergency room countless times for a GI cocktail that still doesn't help the pain. My heart doesn't beat normally.
I also have gastroparesis, which simply means my stomach muscles don't work as well, and food sits in my stomach and takes longer to digest.

I have severe, chronic acid reflux, so much so that if I lean forward or bend over slightly, I get a rush of acid and regurgitation that often times kiss the back of my teeth. I've tried all acid reflux meds, and none of them are working.

It was ultimately a support group that saved my life. 

I went every week for a year and a half, and slowly started to feel my emotions, to allow myself to cry. 

In two months I will celebrate nine years in recovery. 

But it's too late, and my body has suffered.

I started turning grey, worried my professors, who begged me to go into treatment. 

I thought about it, but decided undergrad was more important, and also there was no way I could pay for it. 

I didn't have any friends.

I was utterly consumed.

I purged in gas stations, parks, in my car, behind dumpsters, in ditches and fields, in my room into ziplock gallon size bags, and then discretely hid the bag of vomit in another bag to toss on my way to my poetry class.

I lived off diet coke, diet pills, and pots and pots of coffee. 

On bad days, I would hoard apples, and eat and purge repeatedly until I felt like my heart was going to give out, until the apple cores turned brown, and blood was in the bowl.

I'd like to talk about the long term consequences my eating disorder has had on my body. 

I had a severe eating disorder from ages 12-22, where I was caught in a vicious cycle of starvation/purging. 

When I would eat, say, an apple, or a salad, I would purge it.
